\section*{Lecture 1}
\setcounter{section}{1}
\subsection{The Beginnings}

The goal of these lectures is to introduce the
foundations of the subject of DG-categories before looking at some
examples and applications (such as to quasi-coherent sheaves). To get
to derived categories we typically progress
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}[column sep = small]
    \text{modules} \arrow[r, rightsquigarrow] & \text{resolutions of
      modues} \ar[r, rightsquigarrow] & \text{arbitrary chain
      complexes of modules} \ar[r,rightsquigarrow] & \text{derived
      category}.
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
Typically derived categories take the form of triangulated
categories. We would like something more sophisticated like
DG-categories, or stable $\infty$-categories. We choose DG-categories
for this course. DG-categories, in comparison to triangulated
categories, tend to behave much better when clumped together.

For the rest of these notes fix a ground field $k$.
\begin{remark}
  Most of what is said generalises to commutative rings but you have
  to be careful in some places.
\end{remark}

\begin{definition}
  A DG-category $\cA$ consists of the following data:
  \begin{enumerate}[(1)]
  \item A set of objects.
  \item For any pair of objects $X,Y\in \cA$ a chain complex
    $\Hom_{\cA}(X,Y)\in \Ch(k)$.
  \item For any three objects $X,Y,Z\in \cA$ a map:
    \[ \circ:\Hom_{\cA}(X,Y)\otimes \Hom_{\cA}(Y,Z)\to
      \Hom_{\cA}(X,Z) \] referred to as \emph{composition} such that
    \begin{enumerate}[(i)]
    \item composition is associative
    \item For any $X\in \cA$ there is an element
      $1_X\in \Hom_{\cA}(X,X)$ such that composition with $1_X$ either
      on the left or on the right is the identity. Here we typically
      mean $1_X$ is a zero cycle, $1_X\in Z^0(\Hom_{\cA}(X,X))$.
    \end{enumerate}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{definition}
\begin{question}
  Why do we require $1_X$ to live in degree 0? Do we always assume
  that composition has degree 0?
\end{question}
\begin{remark}
  An example of when taking $k$ to be a commutative ring is more
  subtle is already in the definition of a DG-category -- we want
  $\otimes_k$ to be exact, and so perhaps we would instead want to
  take $\otimes^\bL$ in $(3)$.
\end{remark}
\begin{example}
  (1) Take $\Hom_\cA(X,Y)$ to be concetrated in degree zero. This is a
  $k$-linear category.

  (2) Let $R$ be a ring. Consider $\Ch(R)$ and with
  $\Hom_{\Ch(R)}(M^\bullet,N^\bullet)^s = \prod_r
  \Hom(M^r,N^{r+s})$. If
  $f=(f_t)\in \Hom_{\Ch(R)}(M^\bullet,N^\bullet)^s$ then we define the
  differential as $d_N\circ f+(-1)^s f\circ d_M$. Sometimes we might
  denote this differential as $[d,-]$ where $[-,-]$ should indicate a
  sort of commutator.
An important class of examples is when you have standard complex in
mind for computing $\Ext$. DG-categories make a lot of sense in these
settings since you can define a particular DG-category where the
$\Hom$-complexes are precisely these standard complexes you have in
mind.

(4)  Let $R$ be a ring (by which we will always mean a $k$-algebra)
  and construct a DG-category $\cA$ with objects all $R$-modules, and
  with $\Hom_{\cA}(M,N)$ the bar resolution.
\begin{remark}
  Think about this from the exercises. Do we really need like
  projective flat or something on $M$?
\end{remark}

(4) A classical example which isn't partiularly in the spirit of this
course is to take $k=\bC$, and $\cA$ to have objects the holomorphic
vector bundles on a complex manifold. Then take ??? homsets.

\end{example}

\subsection{Functors between DG-categories}

The naive definition works:
\begin{definition}
  A functor between DG-categories $\cA$ and $\cB$ is:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item a map of sets $\Ob(\cA)\xrightarrow{F}\Ob(\cB)$.
  \item A map $\Hom_\cA(X,Y)\to \Hom_{\cB}(F(X),F(Y))$ which preserves
    the identity and is compatible with composition.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{definition}
Equivalence is kind of subtle however. We can define a strict
equivalence in the normal way: i.e. a functor which is fully faithful
(an isom on homsets) and essentially surjective (every object in the
target is isomorphic to something in the image). This notion is too
restrictive for DG-categories however. For example as in (4) if we
have two different DG-categories corresponding to two different
standard complexes both used to compute the same $\Ext$ groups, then
we want to think of them as the equivalent in a sense.

\begin{definition}
  A quasi-equivalence of DG-categories is a DG-functor $F:\cA\to\cB$
  which is \emph{quasi}-fully faithful, and is
  \emph{quasi}-essentially surjective, i.e. $\Hom_{\cA}(X,Y)\to
  \Hom_{\cB} (F(X),F(Y))$ is a quasi-isomorphism, and for every $Y\in\cB$
  there is an $X\in \cA$ and maps (zero cycles) $F(X)\to Y$ and $Y\to
  F(X)$  which compose to something homotopic to the identity.
\end{definition}

\begin{exercise}
  (1) Consider $\Ho(\cA)$ to have the same objects, but where
  morphisms are $\HH^0(\Hom_\cA(X,Y))$.

  (2) Show a functor $F:\cA\to\cB$ is quasi-essentially surjective if
  and only if $\Ho(F):\Ho(\cA)\to \Ho(\cB)$ is essentially surjective.
\end{exercise}




\section*{Lecture 2}
\setcounter{section}{2}

\begin{example}
  Consider $\cA$ where $\Ob(\cA)=\{\pt\}$ and where
  $\Hom_{\cA}(\pt,\pt)=R$ where $R$ is a DG-algebra.
\end{example}

\begin{Goal}
  Go from $\Ch(R)\to \cD(R)$ for $R\in \Alg_k$.
\end{Goal}

There are two main approaches to constructing $\cD(R)$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Localisation by quisi-isomorphisms. [Drinfeld Quotient Notes]
  \begin{remark}
    localisation refers to inverting morphisms while quotient refers
    to erasing objects so we might be concerned how Drinfeld's
    approach works. However SOMETHING
    $A\to B\to \text{cone}(A\to B)\to\cdots$ SOMETHING. So
    localisation is equivalent to killing all cones of
    quasi-isomorphisms.
  \end{remark}
\item Resolve everything (choose specific standard representatives for
  quasi-isomorphism classes).
\end{enumerate}
\begin{example}
  $\cD^{-}(R)\simeq \Ch^{-}(R)^{\proj}$
\end{example}
